contains the letter 'z', ensuring that 'z' is not at the start or end of the \
word. Here's a function that does this:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\ndef \
match_word_with_z(word):\n    # Regular expression to match a word containing \
'z' not at the start or end\n    pattern = r'^[^z].*z.*[^z]$'\n    return \
bool(re.match(pattern, word))\n\n# Example usage:\n\
print(match_word_with_z(\"crazy\"))  # True\n\
print(match_word_with_z(\"zebra\"))  # False\n\
print(match_word_with_z(\"buzz\"))   # True\n\
print(match_word_with_z(\"pizza\"))  # True\nprint(match_word_with_z(\"z\"))  \
    # False\n```\n\n### Final Answer:\nThe function `match_word_with_z(word)` \
returns `True` if the word contains 'z' not at the start or end; otherwise, \
it returns `False`.Here is a Python function that checks if a given integer \
is a prime number:\n\n```python\ndef is_prime(n):\n    if n <= 1:  # 0 and 1 \
are not prime numbers\n        return False\n    if n <= 3:  # 2 and 3 are \
prime numbers\n        return True\n    if n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:  # \
eliminate multiples of 2 and 3\n        return False\n    i = 5\n    while i \
* i <= n:  # check for factors from 5 to sqrt(n)\n        if n % i == 0 or n \
% (i + 2) == 0:\n            return False\n        i += 6\n    return True\n\
```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. Check if `n` is less than or equal to 1 (not \
prime).\n2. Check if `n` is 2 or 3 (both prime).\n3. Eliminate even numbers \
and multiples of 3.\n4. Use a loop to check for factors from 5 to the square \
root of `n`, skipping even numbers.\n\n### Usage:\nYou can call the function \
`is_prime(n)` with any integer `n` to check if it is prime.Here is a Python \
function that checks whether a sequence of numbers has a decreasing trend:\n\n\
```python\ndef has_decreasing_trend(sequence):\n    if len(sequence) < 2:\n   \
     return False  # Not enough elements to determine a trend\n    return \
all(sequence[i] > sequence[i + 1] for i in range(len(sequence) - 1))\n\n# \
