underscores and underscores with whitespaces using regular expressions:\n\n\
```python\nimport re\n\ndef replace_whitespace_and_underscore(input_string):\n\
    # Replace underscores with a temporary placeholder\n    temp_string = \
re.sub(r'_', '__TEMP__', input_string)\n    # Replace whitespaces with \
underscores\n    temp_string = re.sub(r'\\s+', '_', temp_string)\n    # \
Replace the temporary placeholder with whitespace\n    result_string = \
re.sub(r'__TEMP__', ' ', temp_string)\n    return result_string\n\n# Example \
usage\ninput_str = \"Hello World_this is a test\"\noutput_str = \
replace_whitespace_and_underscore(input_str)\nprint(output_str)  # Output: \
\"Hello_World this is a test\"\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. Replace \
underscores with a temporary placeholder (`__TEMP__`).\n2. Replace all \
whitespace characters with underscores.\n3. Replace the temporary placeholder \
back to whitespace.\n\nThis function will correctly swap underscores and \
whitespaces in the input string.A lucid number is a number that has no \
repeated digits. To find a lucid number that is smaller than or equal to a \
given number \\( n \\), we can create a function in Python. Here\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s how you can implement it:\n\n```python\ndef \
is_lucid(num):\n    \"\"\"Check if a number is a lucid number (no repeated \
digits).\"\"\"\n    digits = str(num)\n    return len(digits) == \
len(set(digits))\n\ndef get_lucid_number(n):\n    \"\"\"Find the largest \
lucid number less than or equal to n.\"\"\"\n    for i in range(n, -1, -1):\n \
       if is_lucid(i):\n            return i\n    return None  # In case \
there are no lucid numbers (which won't happen for non-negative n)\n\n# \
Example usage:\nn = 1234\nprint(get_lucid_number(n))  # This will print the \
