set of its digits.\n2. **get_lucid_number(n)**: This function iterates from \
\\( n \\) down to 0, checking each number to see if it is lucid. It returns \
the first lucid number it finds.\n\nYou can call `get_lucid_number(n)` with \
your desired value of \\( n \\) to get the largest lucid number less than or \
equal to \\( n \\).Here is a Python function that exchanges the position of \
