first and last elements\n    return merged\n\n# Example usage:\n\
lists_of_lists = [[1, 2, 3], ['a', 'b', 'c'], [True, False]]\nresult = \
merge_first_and_last(lists_of_lists)\nprint(result)  # Output: [(1, 3), ('a', \
'c'), (True, False)]\n```\n\nThis function iterates through each sublist, \
retrieves the first and last elements, and appends them as a tuple to the \
`merged` list. It also checks if the sublist is not empty to avoid index \
errors.Here\[CloseCurlyQuote]s a Python function that extracts unique values \
from the values of a given dictionary:\n\n```python\ndef \
