adults (2 tickets):  \n   Cost for adults = 2 \[Times] $109 = $218.\n\n2. \
Calculate the ticket cost for the children (2 tickets with $5 discount each): \
 \n   Discounted price for children = $109 - $5 = $104.  \n   Cost for \
children = 2 \[Times] $104 = $208.\n\n3. Calculate the total cost for the \
family:  \n   Total cost = Cost for adults + Cost for children = $218 + $208 \
= $426.\n\n4. Calculate the change from $500:  \n   Change = $500 - $426 = \
$74.\n\nThe change they will receive is **$74**.To find out how many \
roommates John has, we can follow these steps:\n\n1. Determine how many \
roommates Bob has. According to the problem, Bob has 10 roommates.\n2. \
Calculate twice as many as Bob's roommates: \\( 2 \\times 10 = 20 \\).\n3. \
Since John has five more roommates than twice as many as Bob, we add 5 to the \
previous result: \\( 20 + 5 = 25 \\).\n\nTherefore, John has **25 \
roommates**.Let \\( x \\) be the number of packages delivered by the third \
butcher.\n\nThe weights of the packages from each butcher are as follows:\n- \
First butcher: \\( 10 \\) packages \\( \\times 4 \\) pounds/package = \\( 40 \
\\) pounds\n- Second butcher: \\( 7 \\) packages \\( \\times 4 \\) \
pounds/package = \\( 28 \\) pounds\n- Third butcher: \\( x \\) packages \\( \
\\times 4 \\) pounds/package = \\( 4x \\) pounds\n\nThe total weight of the \
beef delivered by all three butchers is given to be \\( 100 \\) pounds. \
Therefore, we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[\n40 + 28 + 4x = 100\n\\]\n\n\
Now, combine the constants:\n\n\\[\n68 + 4x = 100\n\\]\n\nNext, isolate \\( \
4x \\) by subtracting \\( 68 \\) from both sides:\n\n\\[\n4x = 100 - 68\n\\]\n\
\\[\n4x = 32\n\\]\n\nNow, divide by \\( 4 \\) to solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\[\n\
x = \\frac{32}{4} = 8\n\\]\n\nThus, the third butcher delivered \\( \
\\boxed{8} \\) packages.1. First, calculate the total capacity of the chairs:\
\n   \\[\n   \\text{Total capacity} = 40 \\text{ chairs} \\times 2 \\text{ \
people/chair} = 80 \\text{ people}\n   \\]\n\n2. Determine the number of \
chairs that were not occupied:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Unoccupied chairs} = \
