\n2. **Calculate photos taken on the second day:**\n   - They took 120 more \
photos than the first day.\n   - Photos taken on the second day = \\( 200 + \
120 = 320 \\).\n\n3. **Calculate total photos taken on the trip:**\n   - \
Total photos taken = Photos on the first day + Photos on the second day\n   - \
Total photos taken = \\( 200 + 320 = 520 \\).\n\n4. **Calculate the new total \
in the gallery:**\n   - New total = Original photos + Photos taken on the \
trip\n   - New total = \\( 400 + 520 = 920 \\).\n\nThus, the total number of \
photos in the gallery after the trip is **920**.1. The profit ratio between \
Mike and Johnson is 2:5.\n2. If Johnson received $2500, this represents his \
share (5 parts) of the total profit.\n3. To find the value of one part, \
divide Johnson's share by 5:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Value of one part} = \
\\frac{2500}{5} = 500\n   \\]\n4. Mike's share (2 parts) can be calculated \
as:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Mike's share} = 2 \\times 500 = 1000\n   \\]\n5. After \
spending $200 on a shirt, Mike's remaining amount is:\n   \\[\n   \
\\text{Mike's remaining amount} = 1000 - 200 = 800\n   \\]\n\nFinal answer: \
Mike will have $800 after spending on the shirt."}, {}, None}, "ElementType" -> 
               "String"|>], 
