known as triangular numbers. The nth triangular number can be calculated \
using the formula:\\n\\n\\\\[ T_n = \\\\frac{n(n + 1)}{2} \
\\\\]\\n\\nWhere:\\n- \\\\( n \\\\) is the term's position in the \
sequence.\\n\\nFor example:\\n- For \\\\( n = 1 \\\\): \\\\( T_1 = \
\\\\frac{1(1 + 1)}{2} = 1 \\\\)\\n- For \\\\( n = 2 \\\\): \\\\( T_2 = \
\\\\frac{2(2 + 1)}{2} = 3 \\\\)\\n- For \\\\( n = 3 \\\\): \\\\( T_3 = \
\\\\frac{3(3 + 1)}{2} = 6 \\\\)\\n- For \\\\( n = 4 \\\\): \\\\( T_4 = \
\\\\frac{4(4 + 1)}{2} = 10 \\\\)\\n- For \\\\( n = 5 \\\\): \\\\( T_5 = \
\\\\frac{5(5 + 1)}{2} = 15 \\\\)\\n- For \\\\( n = 6 \\\\): \\\\( T_6 = \
\\\\frac{6(6 + 1)}{2} = 21 \\\\)\\n\\nThus, the series represents the \
triangular numbers, where each term is the sum of the first \\\\( n \\\\) \
natural numbers.\""}}, 
