           GridBox[{{
              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to check if the given integer is a prime \
number.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Here is a Python function that checks if a given integer is \
a prime number:\\n\\n```python\\ndef is_prime(n):\\n    if n <= 1:  # 0 and 1 \
are not prime numbers\\n        return False\\n    if n <= 3:  # 2 and 3 are \
prime numbers\\n        return True\\n    if n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:  # \
eliminate multiples of 2 and 3\\n        return False\\n    i = 5\\n    while \
i * i <= n:  # check for factors from 5 to sqrt(n)\\n        if n % i == 0 or \
n % (i + 2) == 0:\\n            return False\\n        i += 6\\n    return \
True\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. Check if `n` is less than or equal to 1 \
(not prime).\\n2. Check if `n` is 2 or 3 (both prime).\\n3. Eliminate even \
numbers and multiples of 3.\\n4. Use a loop to check for factors from 5 to \
the square root of `n`, skipping even numbers.\\n\\n### Usage:\\nYou can call \
the function `is_prime(n)` with any integer `n` to check if it is prime.\""}},
             GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a function to check if the given integer is a prime \
number."}, {
             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "Here is a Python function that checks if a given integer is a \
prime number:\n\n```python\ndef is_prime(n):\n    if n <= 1:  # 0 and 1 are \
not prime numbers\n        return False\n    if n <= 3:  # 2 and 3 are prime \
numbers\n        return True\n    if n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:  # eliminate \
multiples of 2 and 3\n        return False\n    i = 5\n    while i * i <= n:  \
# check for factors from 5 to sqrt(n)\n        if n % i == 0 or n % (i + 2) \
== 0:\n            return False\n        i += 6\n    return True\n```\n\n### \
Explanation:\n1. Check if `n` is less than or equal to 1 (not prime).\n2. \
Check if `n` is 2 or 3 (both prime).\n3. Eliminate even numbers and multiples \
of 3.\n4. Use a loop to check for factors from 5 to the square root of `n`, \
skipping even numbers.\n\n### Usage:\nYou can call the function `is_prime(n)` \
with any integer `n` to check if it is prime."}}, Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {
