of a number.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Here's a Python function that finds the smallest prime \
divisor of a given number:\\n\\n```python\\ndef smallest_prime_divisor(n):\\n \
   if n <= 1:\\n        return None  # No prime divisor for numbers <= 1\\n   \
 if n % 2 == 0:\\n        return 2  # 2 is the smallest prime number\\n    \
\\n    for i in range(3, int(n**0.5) + 1, 2):\\n        if n % i == 0:\\n     \
       return i  # Found the smallest prime divisor\\n    \\n    return n  # \
If no divisor found, n is prime itself\\n\\n# Example usage\\nnumber = \
56\\nprint(smallest_prime_divisor(number))  # Output: 2\\n```\\n\\nThis \
function checks divisibility starting from the smallest prime (2) and \
proceeds to check odd numbers up to the square root of `n`. If no divisors \
are found, `n` itself is returned as it is prime.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
