              "\"To check if a triangle is valid, we can use the triangle \
inequality theorem, which states that for three sides \\\\( a \\\\), \\\\( b \
\\\\), and \\\\( c \\\\), the following conditions must hold:\\n\\n1. \\\\( a \
+ b > c \\\\)\\n2. \\\\( a + c > b \\\\)\\n3. \\\\( b + c > a \
\\\\)\\n\\nHere's a simple Python function that implements this \
logic:\\n\\n```python\\ndef is_valid_triangle(a, b, c):\\n    return a + b > \
c and a + c > b and b + c > a\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nprint(is_valid_triangle(3, 4, 5))  # Output: \
True\\nprint(is_valid_triangle(1, 2, 3))  # Output: False\\n```\\n\\nThis \
function takes three arguments (the lengths of the triangle's sides) and \
returns `True` if the triangle is valid, and `False` otherwise.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
