module, which provides an efficient way to implement a min-heap.\\n\\nHere\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s a concise implementation:\\n\\n```python\\nimport \
heapq\\n\\ndef process_heap(values):\\n    # Create a min-heap from the input \
values\\n    heap = []\\n    for value in values:\\n        \
heapq.heappush(heap, value)\\n    \\n    # Pop off the smallest values one at \
a time\\n    sorted_values = []\\n    while heap:\\n        smallest = \
heapq.heappop(heap)\\n        sorted_values.append(smallest)\\n    \\n    \
return sorted_values\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nvalues = [5, 2, 9, 1, 5, \
6]\\nsorted_values = process_heap(values)\\nprint(sorted_values)  # Output: \
[1, 2, 5, 5, 6, 9]\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. We import the `heapq` \
module.\\n2. We define the `process_heap` function that takes a list of \
values.\\n3. We create an empty list `heap` to serve as our min-heap.\\n4. We \
push each value into the heap using `heapq.heappush`.\\n5. We pop the \
smallest values from the heap until it is empty, collecting these in \
`sorted_values`.\\n6. Finally, we return the sorted list of values.\""}}, 
