              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To find the nth Bell number, you can use dynamic \
programming. The Bell numbers can be computed using the Bell triangle. Here's \
a Python function to compute the nth Bell number:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
bell_number(n):\\n    # Create a 2D array to store Bell numbers\\n    bell = \
[[0 for _ in range(n+1)] for _ in range(n+1)]\\n    \\n    # Base case\\n    \
bell[0][0] = 1\\n    \\n    # Fill the Bell triangle\\n    for i in range(1, \
n+1):\\n        # First value in each row is the last value of the previous \
row\\n        bell[i][0] = bell[i-1][i-1]\\n        \\n        # Fill the \
rest of the row\\n        for j in range(1, i+1):\\n            bell[i][j] = \
bell[i-1][j-1] + bell[i][j-1]\\n    \\n    # The nth Bell number is found at \
bell[n][0]\\n    return bell[n][0]\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nn = \
5\\nprint(f\\\"The {n}th Bell number is: {bell_number(n)}\\\")\\n```\\n\\n### \
Explanation:\\n1. A 2D list `bell` is created to store the Bell numbers.\\n2. \
The first Bell number (B(0)) is initialized to 1.\\n3. The triangle is filled \
using the recursive relation:\\n   - `bell[i][0] = bell[i-1][i-1]`\\n   - \
`bell[i][j] = bell[i-1][j-1] + bell[i][j-1]`\\n4. Finally, the nth Bell \
number is returned from `bell[n][0]`. \\n\\nYou can replace `n` in the \
example usage with any non-negative integer to find the corresponding Bell \
number.\""}}, GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
