              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"You can find the sum of the XOR of all pairs of numbers in a \
given array by iterating through all possible pairs and calculating their \
XOR. Below is a Python function that does this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
sum_of_xor_pairs(arr):\\n    total_xor_sum = 0\\n    n = len(arr)\\n    \\n   \
 for i in range(n):\\n        for j in range(i + 1, n):\\n            \
total_xor_sum += arr[i] ^ arr[j]\\n    \\n    return total_xor_sum\\n\\n# \
Example usage:\\narray = [1, 2, 3]\\nresult = \
sum_of_xor_pairs(array)\\nprint(result)  # Output: 4 (1^2 + 1^3 + 2^3 = 3 + 2 \
+ 1 = 6)\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. The function `sum_of_xor_pairs` \
takes an array `arr` as input.\\n2. It initializes a variable `total_xor_sum` \
to zero.\\n3. It uses two nested loops to iterate over all unique pairs `(i, \
j)` where `i < j`.\\n4. For each pair, it calculates the XOR using `arr[i] ^ \
arr[j]` and adds this to `total_xor_sum`.\\n5. Finally, it returns the total \
sum of the XORs of all pairs. \\n\\nThis approach has a time complexity of \
O(n^2), which is suitable for small to medium-sized arrays. For larger \
arrays, a more optimized approach may be needed.\""}}, 
